1 Introduction

So far, we have been learning the basics of R. For instance, we have seen how to manipulate matrices and data frames using the apply()-family functions, access to them, modify specific elements, etc. Besides this way to code in R, there is an alternative specially meant to manipulate data frames. This family of R packages belong to what is called tidyverse, and they just try to make these manipulations easier to us and provide functions to do other kind of tasks that wonât be covered in this subject, such as statistical modelling. All these packages share an underlying design philosophy, grammar, and data structures. We have just talked about one: ggplot2. The packages we will covered here follow the same idea.

The objective of this part it to get familiar with some of the functions, but mastering this way of programming takes much more time. If you donât know how to solve a problem using these packages, just try to solve it using R-base, it does not matter! The idea is to add another weapon to your armory.

2 Some comments before starting

2.1 Tidy data

Before starting with some of the functions, we need to introduce tidy data. This is how a dataset has to be structured to work with ggplot2 and other tidyverse packages. Just to put an example, check the image below:

Tidy vs untidy data.

The most important points are:

  1. Every observation of a variable should be in a different row, i.e., each sample must be an individual row.
  2. Each variable should be in a different column, i.e., each feature taken of each individual must be an individual columns.
  3. There should be one table for each type of data.

In the example above, we have a first table in which the column key contains what seem to be two different variables: cases and population. Then, the column value contains the values of each variable. If we were to plot the number of cases vs the population in a scatter plot using ggplot, we couldnât do it because the format is not correct. We make the data tidy by separating these two variables in two different columns, so that each row correspond to each sample (in this case, each country).

You will find many cases where data are not properly structured to work with ggplot2 or other tidyverse packages. I usually carry out these transformations using the reshape2 or tidyr R packages. Not needed now, but keep them in mind if you find this kind of problems, you will see them in further modules.

2.2 Pipes in R

From now on, you will see %>% and |> a lot o times. They are just pipes, like the ones you studied when you learned bash (|). They take whatever is before them, and pass it to the function on the right. Both are equivalent, the only difference is that |> belong to R base (included not a long time ago) and %>% was introduced by the tidyverse R packages. Use the one you most like.

Their objective is to make your code more readable, and allow the possibility to concatenate several functions without having to save intermediate objects.

# the following two expressions are equivalent
x %>% f(y)  
f(x, y)
# these two are also equivalent
y %>% f(x, ., z) 
f(x, y, z )

3 The dplyr R package

Letâs load a dataset to start showing some functions.

dplyr aims to provide functions for basic data manipulations. These verbs can be organised into three categories based on the component of the dataset they work with:

  1. Rows:
  • filter() chooses rows based on column values.
  • slice() chooses rows based on location.
  • arrange() changes the order of the rows.
  1. Columns:
  • select() changes whether or not a column is included.
  • rename() changes the name of columns.
  • mutate() changes the values of columns and creates new columns.
  • relocate() changes the order of the columns.
  1. Groups of rows:
  • group_by() + summarize() collapses a group into a single row.

We wonât use all of them, but the most used for getting familiar with them.

3.4 select()

Instead of rows, select() can pick specific columns. This function is equivalent to access to a data frame using the ways we learnt. It isnât that useful, but when you are operating with dplyr and need to choose specific columns, it allows to do it without creating intermediate variables:

iris %>% arrange(Sepal.Length) %>% select(Species, ID) %>% head()

3.5 mutate()

This is probably the function I use the most. It allows to modify existing and create new columns in a data frame using a syntax very intuitive. Again, you could do the same with R-base:

iris %>% mutate(
  Ratio.Width = Sepal.Width / Petal.Width,
  Rectangular.area.Sepal = Sepal.Width * Sepal.Length,
  Rectangular.area.Petal = Petal.Width * Petal.Length,
) %>% arrange(desc(Rectangular.area.Sepal)) %>% 
  select(Species, Rectangular.area.Sepal) %>% head()
##     Species Rectangular.area.Sepal
## 1 virginica                  30.02
## 2 virginica                  29.26
## 3 virginica                  25.92
## 4    setosa                  25.08
## 5    setosa                  23.20
## 6    setosa                  23.10

In the previous line of code, we have created three new columns that now can be used to do further operations. Now, letâs write the equivalent code in R-base!

We can couple mutate() with case_when(), a generalized version of the ifelse() function. For instance, imagine that now we want to classify these cases according to a categorical variable, and create a column containing that information:

iris.mod <- iris %>% mutate(
  Ratio.Width = Sepal.Width / Petal.Width,
  Class.Ratio.Wdith = case_when(
    Ratio.Width >= mean(Ratio.Width) ~ "Big",
    TRUE ~ "Small"
  )
)
iris.mod %>% head()
##     ID Sepal.Length Sepal.Width Petal.Length Petal.Width Species Ratio.Width Class.Ratio.Wdith
## 1 ID_1          5.1         3.5          1.4         0.2  setosa       17.50               Big
## 2 ID_2          4.9         3.0          1.4         0.2  setosa       15.00               Big
## 3 ID_3          4.7         3.2          1.3         0.2  setosa       16.00               Big
## 4 ID_4          4.6         3.1          1.5         0.2  setosa       15.50               Big
## 5 ID_5          5.0         3.6          1.4         0.2  setosa       18.00               Big
## 6 ID_6          5.4         3.9          1.7         0.4  setosa        9.75               Big

Now, do it using R-base:

Finally, we can use the across() function to modify several columns using only one line of code. No worries if this seems to you a bit complex, it is not needed for this course!

iris.mod %>% mutate(across(c(Petal.Length, Ratio.Width), round)) %>% head()

3.6 Groupping with group_by() and summarize()

With group_by() and summarize(), we can compute grouped statistics according to different columns. They are the equivalents to aggregate() and by() of R-base.

iris.mod %>% group_by(Species) %>% 
  summarize(Mean.Ratio.Width = mean(Ratio.Width))
## # A tibble: 3 Ã 2
##   Species    Mean.Ratio.Width
##   <fct>                 <dbl>
## 1 setosa                16.3 
## 2 versicolor             2.11
## 3 virginica              1.48

We can use more than one column to classify the samples:

iris.mod %>% group_by(Species, Class.Ratio.Wdith) %>% 
  summarize(Mean.Ratio.Width = mean(Ratio.Width))
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'Species'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.
## # A tibble: 4 Ã 3
## # Groups:   Species [3]
##   Species    Class.Ratio.Wdith Mean.Ratio.Width
##   <fct>      <chr>                        <dbl>
## 1 setosa     Big                          16.7 
## 2 setosa     Small                         6.22
## 3 versicolor Small                         2.11
## 4 virginica  Small                         1.48

We can just count the number of samples according to the groups we have just created.

iris.mod %>% group_by(Species, Class.Ratio.Wdith) %>% summarize(N_samples = n())
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'Species'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.
## # A tibble: 4 Ã 3
## # Groups:   Species [3]
##   Species    Class.Ratio.Wdith N_samples
##   <fct>      <chr>                 <int>
## 1 setosa     Big                      48
## 2 setosa     Small                     2
## 3 versicolor Small                    50
## 4 virginica  Small                    50

We can also summarize several columns at the same time using the across function:

iris.mod %>% group_by(Species, Class.Ratio.Wdith) %>% 
  summarize(across(starts_with("Sepal"), ~mean(.x, na.rm = T)))

3.7 Combining different data frames

According to the tidy format, it is very typical to store your data in different tables. If we need to merge them to make a plot (for instance), we need to correctly align the two tables, otherwise we would be mixing information belonging to different samples. This is done by merge() in R-base and by left_join() (and the rest of alike functions) in tidyverse. Letâs put some examples from this article (https://dplyr.tidyverse.org/articles/two-table.html):

library("nycflights13")
flights2 <- flights %>% select(year:day, hour, origin, dest, tailnum, carrier)

In this datasset, data are separated into different data frames:

3.7.1 Types of join

So far, we have been keeping all the information on the left data frame, and appending (if possible) the information coming from the right one. However, we could keep only the shared elements between the two data frames, or keeping all the entries coming from the two data frames. This is done using the inner_join(), right_join(), and full_join() functions. Check the documentation and see their differences!

Also, check the merge() function (R-base version for these operations).

3.7.2 Merging two data frames containing the same information.

Check the following functions: intersect(), union(), and setdiff() (from the dplyr R package). They expect a data frame with the same structure, and will give you a data frame with the wanted combination depending on the function. See the following figure to get an intuition about them:

intersect(), union(), and setdiff() functions.

3.8 About tidyverse vs R-base

From my view, tidyverse (and specifically, dplyr) is just an alternative that makes life easier many times. However, this does not mean that you should only learn this way of coding in R and forget about R-base. There will be countless situations where tidyverse wonât be the best solution or simply a valid solution. For instance, these functions are pretty handy to work with data frames, but they cannot handle (or at least the functions we have talked about in this course) sparse matrices, a special type of matrix where the most frequent entry is zero (no worries, we will talk about them in the future).

We are talking about these functions because I think learning R without mentioning them does not make sense nowadays, but please, learn the R basics we previously covered, you will need it! Check this link for a comparison between dplyr and R-base: https://dplyr.tidyverse.org/articles/base.html.
